Learning virtual threads is essentially about unlearning the habit of "hoarding" threads. Since you're looking to master this step-by-step,
we should start from the syntax and move into enterprise-grade implementation.

Step 1: Environmental Setup
Virtual threads were finalized in Java 21. Ensure your environment is ready:
 * JDK: Install JDK 21 or later.
 * Build Tool: If using Maven or Gradle, ensure your compiler target is set to 21.
 * IDE: Use a modern version of IntelliJ IDEA or Eclipse that supports Project Loom features.

Step 2: Creating Your First Virtual Thread
There are two primary ways to create a single virtual thread. Unlike platform threads, 
these are not active by default upon creation unless you use the .start() method.
// Method A: Using the Thread builder
Thread vThread = Thread.ofVirtual()
        .name("worker-", 1)
        .start(() -> {
            System.out.println("Running on: " + Thread.currentThread());
        });

// Method B: Using an unstarted thread (useful for custom scheduling)
Thread unstarted = Thread.ofVirtual().unstarted(() -> {
    System.out.println("I haven't started yet!");
});
unstarted.start();

Step 3: Moving to the ExecutorService
In a real-world backend, you rarely manage individual threads. You use an ExecutorService. Java 21 introduced a specialized executor that creates a new virtual thread for every task.
try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
    executor.submit(() -> {
        // Simulating a blocking I/O call (e.g., calling a REST API)
        Thread.sleep(Duration.ofSeconds(1));
        return "Task Complete";
    });
} // AutoCloseable ensures all threads finish before exiting the block

Step 4: Integrating with Spring Boot 3.2+
If you are working with Spring Boot, you don't need to manually configure bean executors anymore. 
Starting from Spring Boot 3.2, you can enable virtual threads with a single property in your application.properties:
spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true

What this does:
 * Configures Tomcat/Jetty to use virtual threads for handling web requests.
 * Configures @Async methods to run on virtual threads.
 * Configures Task Schedulers to use virtual threads.

Step 5: Handling "Thread Pinning"
This is the most critical "gotcha" for senior developers. A virtual thread can get "pinned" to its carrier (OS) thread, meaning the OS thread can't be released while waiting for I/O. This happens when:
 * Executing code inside a synchronized block or method.
 * Calling a native method (JNI).
The Solution: Replace synchronized with java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock in your utility classes and shared services.

Step 6: Observability
Because you might have 100,000 threads running, traditional thread dumps are unreadable.
 * JDK Flight Recorder (JFR): Use this to monitor virtual thread pinning and scheduling.
 * New Thread Dump Format: Use jcmd <pid> Thread.dump_to_file -format=json <file> to get a modern, parseable view of your thread state.
Step 7: Structured Concurrency (Preview Feature)
If you want to go deeper, look into Structured Concurrency. It treats multiple tasks running in different threads as a single unit of work, 
ensuring that if one sub-task fails, the others are cancelled automatically.
// This is currently a preview feature in Java 21/22
try (var scope = new StructuredTaskScope.ShutdownOnFailure()) {
    Subtask<String> user = scope.fork(() -> fetchUser());
    Subtask<Integer> order = scope.fork(() -> fetchOrder());

    scope.join();           // Join both forks
    scope.throwIfFailed();  // Propagate errors

    System.out.println(user.get() + " ordered " + order.get());
}

